A free expansion into a vacuum is highly irreversible. Because system boundaries are insulated and expand into zero resistance, $Q = 0$ and $W = 0$, leading to $Delta U = 0$. For an ideal gas, this dictates that temperature is perfectly constant ($Delta T = 0$). 
  
  Entropy is a state function; hence, its value change can be calculated along an alternate virtual reversible isothermal path:
  $ Delta S_"gas" = n R ln(V_2 / V_1) = 2 " mol" times 8.314 " J mol"^(-1) "K"^(-1) times ln(3) = 18.27 " J/K" $
  
  Because the process is adiabatic and does not affect the surroundings, $Delta S_"surroundings" = 0$. Consequently:
  $ Delta S_"universe" = Delta S_"gas" + Delta S_"surroundings" = 18.27 + 0 = 18.27 " J/K" $